[Given Scenario]
Citigroup (C) is a bank stock that has struggled since the Great Recession but is now showing signs of improvement under CEO Jane Fraser. The stock trades at 82% of its tangible book value (TBV) or net worth, a discount that may be due to its inefficient organization and lackluster returns in the past. However, Fraser has made significant changes, including selling or exiting 14 international consumer franchises and announcing the divestiture of its Mexico division. The bank has also begun to repurchase shares, which will be accretive to TBV. Analysts are now more optimistic about earnings improvement, driven by higher-returning businesses in credit card lending, investment banking, and international cash management services. The stock has a 3% dividend yield, providing compensation for investors to wait. Billionaires Warren Buffett and Stanley Druckenmiller have taken stakes in Citigroup, with Buffett increasing his stake in 2023 and Druckenmiller purchasing over 327,000 shares in the third quarter. The environment for banking is expected to improve with a steepening yield curve, de-regulation, and lighter capital requirements.
